DOORCONV01 = "\cQNotification";
DOORCONV02 = "\cCThis door can't be opened, as indicated by its grey color. The appearance of doors will help you explore the maps by distinguishing areas worth being investigated from less important areas, which are simply not accessible. \n\n\cCFor instance, \cUgrey\cC wood doors or metal doors with \cUlittle locks\cC can't be accessed at all. On the other hand, \cEbrown\cC wood doors, or light grey metal doors, can always be opened. However, locked doors with a colored knob require the appropriate keys. Keeping this information in mind will save you a lot of time and frustration during your missions!";

CAMPPRISCONV01 = "\cQItzhak Stern";
CAMPPRISCONV02 = "\cCYou don't look too good. The Nazis beat you up pretty good... I guess they wouldn't treat a snooper of their own in such a way so you won't be a treat for our last hope for escape.\n\n\cCDid you arrive with the other prisoners? I haven't see you here before, boy...";
CAMPPRISCONV03 = "\cCI am William Blazkowicz";
CAMPPRISCONV04 = "\cCYou must be kidding... do you really think you can make it out of this alive? Don't you think we already try to find a way now for months? We collect anything that might be of good use to us for an insurrection, scattered hidden around the whole camp - \cFbushes\cC, \cFbeds\cC... we knew we can't make it through the main gates but one of our fellow sufferers, Poldek Pfefferberg, was able to copy the \cFkey\cC to the back entrance of the main office... the SS took him 3 nights ago though, I think he is dead and laying in one of the mass graves, and with him the key is gone... \n\nBut now that \cRHitler\cC has ordered the <<final solution>>, we can't waste any more time... do you know what this means? If we don't make it out of this, we are dead. All of us. We are digging with our last power, we are fatigue, we are desperate...\n\n\cCIf you want to help us, grab the shovel and simply start digging with us for the dead... -- or what are your plans?";
CAMPPRISCONV05 = "\cCI go for the living";
CAMPPRISCONV06 = "\cQStefan Spielberg";
CAMPPRISCONV07 = "\cCPlease... don't talk to me, it's too dangerous. The guards from the tower kill us with their snipers if we stop working and talk with other... go away!!";
CAMPPRISCONV08 = "\cQWilek Chilowicz";
CAMPPRISCONV09 = "\cCYou are new, aren't you? Blazkowicz is your name you say?\n\n\We've served together in Poland during the Blitzkrieg and I was captivated after the fall of Warschau. I am here now already for a long time, and it's more of luck that I am still alive than anything else... alive.. yes, if you can call that alive.\n\nBut hope is not forsaken yet!";
CAMPPRISCONV10 = "\cCWhy?";
CAMPPRISCONV11 = "\cCWe are taking the reins my friend.\n\n\cQItzhak Stern\cC, one of my imprisoned friends is planning an escape. They started to dig below the camp and they are trying to reach the outside somehow.\n\nThey are currently suffering problems because of the water ditch around the camp so progress got slower, but we are doing our best.\n\nYou should talk to him, he is in the western part of the camp. You can get there through a \cFsmall hole\cC below the fence, just watch out.";
CAMPPRISCONV12 = "\cQNigel Rowand";
CAMPPRISCONV13 = "\cCGo away! There is nothing to see here!";
CAMPPRISCONV14 = "\cQJosef Liepold";
CAMPPRISCONV15 = "\cCHave you seen the drums over there?\n\nNo idea what it is but they are getting charges of full containers every second day, and every other day, empty barrels were taken. I wonder what they do with that substance...";
CAMPPRISCONV16 = "\cQMietek Pemper";
CAMPPRISCONV17 = "\cCSsssh... silent, listen... you arrived with the new prisoners? So many of them... but don't worry, it won't take long until we have free beds again.\n\nThe SS Officers are examining the people each week. And each week the sick and weak ones were taken into the main building... I have never seen one of them returning. I guess we can't even imagine what terrible tests they have to bear.\n\nIf you are one of the lucky ones, you will die before leaving and end up in the mass graves... oh may god be with us...";
CAMPPRISCONV18 = "\cQManuel Bernstein";
CAMPPRISCONV19 = "\cCOh... are you here to rescue us? To get us out? \n\nI will tell you a secret: We waited a long time for someone, or even for getting out of this on our own. I have gathered some equipment the \cRKrauts\cC have lost or that I simply stole when they were sleeping.\n\nI hid all of it under a field nearby, you should check it out, it will be of use to you.\n\nGod bless you!";
CAMPPRISCONV20 = "\cCRadio transmission";
CAMPPRISCONV21 = "\cCWe don't have a radio down here and all of the radios from the camp headquarter are connected with each other, there is no chance to do a transmission without a \cRKraut\cC noticing it.\n\nThough, in the watchhouse near the eastern gate, the SS Officer has a portable one. If you can somehow get him out of the way, you might get in contact with your comerades unnoticed. But be careful: Don't let anyone hear him dying, so close the door behind you!";
CAMPPRISCONV22 = "\cCCan you repeat that?";

GENERICSOLDIERMESSAGE01 =  "\cQInfantry Soldier\n\cPCpt. \cCglad to see the cavalry is coming. We god ambushed by a \cRTiger\cC tank at this little east of us. We can give you cover, just take out that tank for us so we can reach our division.";

MEDICCONV01 = "\cQLt. Ty 'Bones' Halderman";
MEDICCONV02 = "\cCCaptain, any wounds I need to take care of?";
MEDICCONV03 = "\cCYes, please.";
MEDICCONV04 = "\cQYou're looking fine again, sir.";
MEDICCONV05 = "\cCWelcome back, \cPCpt. Blazkowicz\cC; it's an honor for me to finally meet you in person. I've heard a few stories about you and your bravery in the field. And your salary, for that matter! Oh, but pardon my manners. My name is \cQLt. Ty Halderman\cC, but most know me as \cQBones\cC since I'm the medic around here. It's my job to patch you up if you come back from a mission with any scratches or scrapes! Welcome to headquarters, sir!";
MEDICCONV06 = "\cCNice to meet you too, Lt.";
MEDICCONV07 = "\cCWelcome back, \cPCpt. Blazkowicz\cC! We all knew that prison wouldn't be able to hold you for long! ...well, I have to admit, a few of the boys doubted that we'd see you again, but \cQCpt. Blake\cC kept saying that not a single Kraut on the continent could take you down - and he was damn right!";
MEDICCONV08 = "\cCThank you, Lt.";
MEDICCONV09 = "\cCCpt., may I speak frankly to you? Regrets to the loss of \cQCpt. Blake\cC. If I could revive him from the dead, I'll do it, no matter the costs.\n\n\cCWe have lost so many brave men already, sometimes I feel just powerless. On the other hand, we have already rescued so many more... this keeps me alive, keeps me motivated, we are still doing so much for those people out there, it's not the right moment to loose courage, sir!";
MEDICCONV10 = "\cCThank you, Lt., you are right.";

BARKEEPERCONV01 = "\cQJuliette 'Shotglass' Bertrand";
BARKEEPERCONV02 = "\cCBonjour, mon ami! It's been too long! I'm sad to say zat I have much work to do at ze moment, but we will catch up another day. I have a good chardonnay we can share, perhaps with a little flirting, as in ze old times, oui? I've missed you...";
BARKEEPERCONV03 = "\cCBonjour, mon ami. I'm told we will rendezvous on your next operation. I am still part of \cQLa Resistance\cC; I've made sure ze \cQGeneral\cC knows zat! He agreed zat I will meet up with ze rebels in Paris to gather intelligence on ze \cRNazi\cC forces. Zere is a hideout where we will wait for you. Once you infiltrate Paris, you will meet up with us, and I will - comment on dit? - 'fill you in.' On ze situation in ze city, I mean, so stop smiling like zat! Ze \cQGeneral\cC will tell you more. Oh, you are worried about me? You shouldn't be! Have you forgotten, mon cher, zat *I* am ze troublemaker? It is ze *Germans* who should worry!";
BARKEEPERCONV04 = "\cCEt voila, here we are again. We had an exciting time in ze field, oui? I can't wait until ze next time, mon cher. Take care, and bonne chance, \cPWilliam\cC!";
BARKEEPERCONV05 = "\cCOh mon cher, I was almost dying... I'm overjoyed to see you unharmed! I heard zat \cQDouglas\cC helped you escape ze prison; I must remember to give him a hug and a kiss for bringing you back to me. How are you?";
BARKEEPERCONV06 = "\cCThanks, Juliette. I am fine.";
BARKEEPERCONV07 = "\cCIt's wonderful to have you back! But ze mood here at HQ is certainly changing lately. I haven't had much time to take care of ze mess hall zese few weeks since your capture... it drove me mad! But zat's not ze only problem.\n\n\cCMon ami, zere is a spy among us. Ze top \cQAllied Headquarters\cC officials seem certain zat it is \cQGutenberg\cC, and zey are already investigating his lab. We have not exactly been welcoming toward him, even after all ze work he did, so perhaps he regretted betraying his country, and figured zey would forgive him in exchange for \cQAllied\cC intel... but, mon Dieu, I'm still so shocked and disappointed! I simply can't believe he's ze spy... could it be zat someone is framing him?\n\n\cCIt saddens me zat walking zese familiar halls should feel so strange, but you can feel how HQ has changed. Everyone seems distant, suspicious. Zere is no trust. All I can say is, be attentive and stay cautious. Please take care of yourself, my dear \cPWilliam\cC.";
BARKEEPERCONV08 = "\cCMon cher, I am very happy to see you again. How are you?\n\n\cCI have to tell you something important: It was not \cQGutenberg\cC! The \cQMP\cC are still investigating his laboratory, but it's clear now that he has a good alibi and there is nothing that can prove he is guilty. I am happy to hear this. Yes, he is german, but I knew his heart is in the right place. \n\n\cCBut this also means the traitor is still around. Mon ami, please be careful on your next missions, you will be in my heart, and bonne chance!";
BARKEEPERCONV09 = "\cCMon cher, how do you feel? Do you still have those nightmares? Words can't describe how much I suffer from his loss...\n\n\cQDouglas\cC was a good friend of mine too, but I know that our friendship was never as tight as yours, \cPWilliam\cC. I am so sorry...  but please try not to do anything reckless or dangerous. I don't want to lose you too...";
BARKEEPERCONV10 = "\cCI will avenge Douglas.";
BARKEEPERCONV11 = "\cCI know you want to avenge him, and I am sure everyone at the HQ wants to.\n\n\cCBut, \cPWilliam\cC, you shouldn't lose your mind dwelling on his death. \cQDouglas\cC wouldn't have wanted to see you in such a mood or do something suicidal just for ze sake of killing \cRRyan\cC.\n\n\cCHow could we have been so blind all this time? It was him for such a long time, and we didn't notice anything... I feel like such an idiot...\n\n\cCWell, \cQGeneral Miller\cC is already waiting for you in the briefing room, but you should also visit Lieutenant \cQAnthony F. Arlow\cC in the room to your left; He has a special job for you. \n\nIt seems we don't even have ze time for sorrow just now... mon cher, I will be here for you, just let me know when you need me.";

// Deprecated - BARKEEPERMESSAGEXX is now used on C1M5.
BARKEEPERLIVE01 = "\cCBonsoir, mon ami. I am glad to see you alive. I knew my secret mechanism wouldn't fool you; you are too clever! But enough chatter, we must hurry! Ze \cRNazis\cC are preparing to destroy ze plaza bridge as we speak. You must not let zem! Ze enemy firmly holds ze plaza; you will find not only many on ze ground, but snipers above as well. After you save ze bridge, you must take out zese forces. Zen, you can explore and secure ze nearby buildings - we know ze enemy has connected ze \cBhotel\cC to ze catacombs, so start there. And remember, ze \cRGermans\cC won't just *give* us \cBParis\cC; zey could counter at any moment, so be ready to hold ze plaza until our *own* \cQreinforcements\cC arrive. We'll hold our position here and watch for ze enemy. I will stay in radio contact with \cQCpt. Blake\cC - he will keep you updated.";
BARKEEPERLIVE02 = "\cPWilliam\cC, zere are \cFmachine guns\cC up zere in ze streets, left over from ze fighting. Zese guns could be of good use to you, especially when ze enemy tries to retake the plaza. Remember zat you must not only hold the plaza but also defend zat \cFNebelwerfer\cC gun - it would be of much help to ze Allies, but only if we can bring it back to HQ in one piece, and ze \cRGermans\cC would prefer to destroy it! Oh, and while we speak of danger: Be alert in ze catacombs. \cBParis\cC' underground has seen... better days, and zere are all kinds of - how do you say? - 'critters' down zere. In fact, zere should be an old entrance to ze catacombs near zis hideout. Maybe it is related to ze odd keyhole just outside? Anyway, mon cher, stay alive - et bonne chance!";

BARKEEPERLIVEANSWER01 = "\cCAnything else?";
BARKEEPERLIVEANSWER02 = "\cCCan you repeat that?";

BARKEEPERMESSAGE01 = "\cEJuliette\n\cCBonsoir, mon ami. I knew my secret mechanism wouldn't fool you; Bon travail! But, you must hurry. Take this key, and get ready to defuse ze bombs on ze main bridge! \cQMe\cC and \cQDouglas\cC will keep you up to date on ze situation. Allez maintenant, vite!";
BARKEEPERMESSAGE02 = "\cEJuliette\n\cCWhat are you doing, mon ami? Hurry up and defuse ze bombs on ze main bridge!";
BARKEEPERMESSAGE03 = "\cEJuliette\n\cCWhat are you doing, mon ami? Go grab one of those machine guns on ze streets, and hold ze plaza for our forces!";
BARKEEPERMESSAGE04 = "\cEJuliette\n\cCBon travail! Now, find a way out of there, and bring that skull key back to my hideout.";
BARKEEPERMESSAGE05 = "\cEJuliette\n\cCOkay. See ze skull key slot, mon ami? The \cBParis catacombs\cC are behind that door. Watch your step; ze catacombs are filled with \cRnasty critters\cC like \cRbats\cC and \cRrats\cC. Stay alert, and keep your weapons ready.";
BARKEEPERMESSAGE06 = "#UNUSED#";
BARKEEPERMESSAGE07 = "\cEJuliette\n\cCKeep clearing out ze plaza and any other buildings you can get in to. There must be another way into ze catacombs.";
BARKEEPERMESSAGE08 = "\cEJuliette\n\cCKeep searching ze catacombs, mon ami. Look for an entrance into ze casino. Once you've found your way out of one of there, you should be able to finish clearing out ze bank and museum.";
BARKEEPERMESSAGE09 = "\cEJuliette\n\cCBon travail le cherche du disc soleil, mon ami! Keep it with you, mon ami, and keep searching for a way into ze casino. Maybe you'll find ze other half in one of those buildings, non?"; // After finding solar disc
BARKEEPERMESSAGE10 = "\cEJuliette\n\cCTres bien, mon ami! \cBParis\cC is ours again, and ze \cRNazis\cC are retreating. As soon as we get back to HQ, I'll pour \cPyou\cC and \cQDouglas\cC a glass of my finest wine, oui? Hehe, you deserve it.";

AFADOOMERCONV01 = "\cQLt. Anthony F. Arlow";
AFADOOMERCONV02 = "\cCGreetings, \cPCpt. Blazkowicz\cC. My name is \cQLt. Anthony F. Arlow\cC. I am the communications officer, and I am at your service. I am sure you have heard enough condolences already, so I'm going to cut straight to the chase.";
AFADOOMERCONV03 = "\cCGo on, Lt.";
AFADOOMERCONV04 = "\cCSure, \cPCpt.\cC. In addition to destroying the concentration camp, I have another objective for you that would help us find out \cRHitler\cC's plans, and what his Endlösung actually means.\n\nThe key seems to be the concentration camp near Dachau. If you, by any chance, have the opportunity to collect some \cFinformation\cC about the scientific research projects at the camp, please do so. If you find at least \cF6 clues\cC, I am sure I can solve the puzzle.\n\nThanks in advance for your help, \cPCaptain\cC!";
AFADOOMERCONV05 = "\cCGood news, \cPCpt.\cC. With your help, I was able to complete my report. As good as this is, it makes the overall situation much worse. I suggest you talk to \cQGeneral Miller\cC now. We will meet again later. I will accompany you in the next mission.";
AFADOOMERCONV06 = "Thanks for your support, \cPCpt.\cC, but you didn't find enough clues for me to complete my report. It's more of a mystery now than it was before, and things will definitely get harder for you, but moaning won't help. We need to look forward.\n\nGood luck, we will talk later.";

AFADOOMERMESSAGE01 = "\cQLt. Anthony F. Arlow\n\cCGood work, \cPCpt.\cC You've found enough clues for me to solve the puzzle and complete my report. Bring that stuff back to HQ.";

BARRANDICONV01 = "\cQLt. Randi Heit";
BARRANDICONV02 = "\cCWelcome back, sir, can I \cU*hic*\cC ...serve you anything? Or perhaps regale you ... \cU*hic*\cC with a fascinating story, from the multitude of interesting experiences I ... \cU*hic*\cC ...had during my time at sea?";
BARRANDICONV03 = "\cCI am Lt. Randi Heit from the U.S. Marine Corps, second batallion \cU*hic*\cC ...or maybe the third, or fifth... I stopped... \cU*hic*\cC ...counting after a while.";
BARRANDICONV04 = "\cCErm... who are you?";
BARRANDICONV05 = "\cCWhat's your background?";
BARRANDICONV06 = "\cCWell, I was... \cU*hic*\cC ... busy with erm... other things in the past two decades, and not necessarily my obligations ... \cU*hic*\cC ... but now, I find different ways to help out with intel. I happen to be quite gifted in the domain of technology, computing machines, you know - all the crazy things that are in develop-- ... \cU*hic*\cC ... in development these days. A couple of years ago, I even assisted Konrad Zuse's research but, well... one or two drinks got in between things... and now, here I am, at your service, \cPCaptain\cC, be it gathering intel or assisting with technical issues! But pardon me, sir, these drinks won't serve themselves! We'll speak another time.";
BARRANDICONV07 = "\cCEvening, sir, care to have a good stout drink with me? No? Well, maybe that's for the best... this seems like the first time in ages that I'm not hung over!\n\n\cCI've been hearing about your recent efforts near the \cBBlack Forest\cC... These gents sure get talkative after seven or eight beers, even the high-ranking fellows!\n\n\cCI've worked with the kind of technology you discovered in that facility. In bygone days I was part of a special group of engineers, researching and developing weapons for the U.S. Air Corps. No matter how many breakthroughs we made, the German engineers were always a step ahead, and what you saw in that facility proves it still holds true.\n\n\cCSir, pardon my frankness, but you should come touch base with me every now and then - I'll be keeping my eyes and ears open, and I just might learn something you'd like to hear. But now: time for a drink! Hell, I'm damn near sober!";
BARRANDICONV08 = "\cCGood morning sirrrrr... \cU*hic*\cC ...or good evening? No idea how... \cU*hic*\cC ...late it currently is...\n\n\cCNews? Oh well... \cU*hic*\cC ...you caught me in a very gooo-\cU*hic*\cC-ood condition my friend... I'll tell you something if you don't \cU*hic*\cC ... you don't tell anyone elseeey: \cU*hic*\cC ... \cRThor's Hammer\cC isn't only the ... \cU*hic*\cC ...name of Nazi thingie... it is also the name of... \cU<whistles>\cC the long dong between my legs, hahaha \cU*hic*\cC ... ugh ... I think the last shot was spoiled... \cU*hic*\cC";
BARRANDICONV09 = "\cCExcuse me, sir! The last time we talked, I wasn't exactly in touch with my senses; sorry about that. I promise that won't happen again... or at least, not so frequently.\n\n\cCBut, to make up for it, I have some valuable information for you: Your next mission is only the peak of \cRThor's Hammer\cC, I promise you this. I have no idea what the staff will tell you, or have already told you, but I am reading between the lines, believe me... all the facilities -- \cREisenmann\cC, \cRFeuerdrone\cC and the upcoming \cRStahlhimmel\cC -- they seem to be hiding something else, or leading us on a false path.\n\n\cCKeep an eye out for clues during your upcoming mission - search every single room, and you will find the clues I'm talking about!";
BARRANDICONV10 = "\cCEh? Didn't I tell you? All the technology that is lightyears ahead, all the research on ... \cU*hic*\cC ...the moon, and the huge flying saucer... I have no idea what the Nazis were doing there, but maybe they are already considering a second Endlösung if their first ... \cU*hic*\cC ... their first one isn't successful ... I mean, 'New Berlin', what the heck?!...\n\n\cCI heard you've been collecting \cFMayan Artifacts\cC for \cQProfessor Gutenberg\cC for a while now. Believe it or not, call me a drunken idiot but \cU*hic*\cC ... Long before the first European explorers set foot in the new world, the Aztecs and Maya were already advanced civilizations. Where did they get their wisdom? The technology?... \cU*hic*\cC\n\n\cCI think there is much more hidden in the jungles. The \cRNazis\cC already believe in that; Maybe they are looking into this ancient technology for a way to change things that are out of our control... like space or time \cU*hic*\cC... \n\n\cCYou should really talk to Gutenberg now if you have found all of the \cFArtifacts\cC before it is too late... \cU*hic*\cC ... want to have a drink now?";

